							<h3>2) Video Preparation</h3>
							<p><img src="img/videoprep.png" alt="video prep"></p>
							<p>
								To run a video in PyTrack you must first rip it into a folder of images in a sequential order. PyTrack will accept any image format that PyGame will: JPG, PNG, 
								GIF (non animated), BMP, PCX, TGA (uncompressed), TIF, LBM (and PBM), PBM (and PGM, PPM), and XPM. We suggest that you use <a href="http://www.irfanview.com/">Irfanview</a>,
								and you can find a tutorial on how to rip the images from a video <a href="javascript://">here</a>.
							</p>
						</div>
						<div class="span4">
							<h3>3) Running</h3>
							<p><img src="img/batchtracking.png" alt="running"></p>
							<p>
								Use the PyTrack manager to tell PyTrack that there is a new image folder to process. From there you can set configurations and tolerances. From the manager you can also
								view the tracked images, as well as output tracking results to a file. A tutorial on how to do this is <a href="javascript://">here</a>.
							</p>
